# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: statistical-mechanics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] In statistical mechanics and mathematics, a **Boltzmann distribution** (also called **Gibbs distribution**) is a probability distribution or probability measure that gives the probability that a system will be in a certain state as a function of that state's energy and the temperature of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The symbol $\propto$ denotes proportionality (see § The distribution for the proportionality constant).
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The term *system* here has a wide meaning; it can range from a collection of "sufficient number" of atoms or a single atom to a macroscopic system such as a natural-gas storage tank.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] Therefore, the Boltzmann distribution can be used to solve a wide variety of problems.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The distribution shows that states with lower energy will always have a higher probability of being occupied.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution is named after Ludwig Boltzmann, who first formulated it in 1868 during his studies of the statistical mechanics of gases in thermal equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution should not be confused with the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution or Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution gives the probability that a system will be in a certain *state* as a function of that state's energy, while the Maxwell–Boltzmann distributions give the probabilities of particle *speeds* or *energies* in ideal gases.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The distribution of energies in a *one-dimensional* gas, however, does follow the Boltzmann distribution.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution is a probability distribution that gives the probability of a certain state as a function of that state's energy and temperature of the system to which the distribution is applied.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] It results from the constraint that the probabilities of all accessible states must add up to 1.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] (These special cases occur when the mean value is either the minimum or maximum of the energies εi.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The partition function can be calculated if we know the energies of the states accessible to the system of interest.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] For atoms the partition function values can be found in the NIST Atomic Spectra Database.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The distribution shows that states with lower energy will always have a higher probability of being occupied than the states with higher energy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] It also gives the quantitative relationship between the probabilities of the two states being occupied.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The corresponding ratio of populations of energy levels must also take their degeneracies into account.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution is often used to describe the distribution of particles, such as atoms or molecules, over bound states accessible to them.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] For a system consisting of many particles, the probability of a particle being in state i is practically the probability that picking a random particle from that system will find it in state i.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution gives these probability for a system in thermal equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] This equation is of great importance to spectroscopy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] Spectroscopy observes spectral lines of atoms or molecules undergoing transitions from one state to another.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] In order for this to be possible, there must be some particles in the first state to undergo the transition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] Their fraction can be estimated from the Boltzmann distribution.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] If it is negligible, the transition is very likely not observed at the temperature for which the calculation was done.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] In general, a larger fraction of molecules in the first state means a higher number of transitions to the second state.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] However, there are other factors that influence the intensity of a spectral line, such as whether it is caused by an allowed or a forbidden transition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution is a special case of the generalized Boltzmann distribution.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The generalized Boltzmann distribution is used in statistical mechanics to describe canonical ensemble, grand canonical ensemble and isothermal–isobaric ensemble.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The generalized Boltzmann distribution is usually derived from the principle of maximum entropy, but there are other derivations.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution appears in statistical mechanics when considering closed systems of fixed composition that are in thermal equilibrium (equilibrium with respect to energy exchange).
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The most general case is the probability distribution for the canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The canonical ensemble has a state probability distribution with the Boltzmann form.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] of a given subsystem state, among the collection.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The canonical ensemble has the property of separability when applied to such a collection: as long as the non-interacting subsystems have fixed composition, then each subsystem's state is independent of the others and is also characterized by a canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] statistical frequency distribution of subsystem states has the Boltzmann form.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] In particle systems, many particles share the same space and regularly change places with each other; the single-particle state space they occupy is a shared space.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] gas of non-interacting particles at equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] This expected number distribution has the Boltzmann form.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution can be introduced to allocate permits in emissions trading.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] A new allocation method, known as the Boltzmann Fair Division, uses the Boltzmann distribution to describe the most probable, natural, and unbiased distribution of emission permits among multiple countries.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] This framework has been further extended to address general problems of distributive justice, including cake-cutting and resource allocation, by allowing flexibility in how factors such as contribution, need, or preference are weighted.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann fair division is recognized for providing a simple yet powerful probabilistic model that can be adapted to various social, political, and economic contexts.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution has the same form as the multinomial logit model.
[src:statistical-mechanics/boltzmann-distribution] As a discrete choice model, this is very well known in economics since Daniel McFadden made the connection to random utility maximization.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In statistical mechanics, a **canonical ensemble** is the statistical ensemble that represents the possible states of a mechanical system in thermal equilibrium with a heat bath at a fixed temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The system can exchange energy with the heat bath, so that the states of the system will differ in total energy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The principal thermodynamic variable of the canonical ensemble, determining the probability distribution of states, is the absolute temperature (symbol: *T*).
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The ensemble typically also depends on mechanical variables such as the number of particles in the system (symbol: *N*) and the system's volume (symbol: *V*), each of which influence the nature of the system's internal states.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] An ensemble with these three parameters, which are assumed constant for the ensemble to be considered canonical, is sometimes called the ***NVT* ensemble**.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] where *E* is the total energy of the microstate, and *k* is the Boltzmann constant.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The number *F* is the free energy (specifically, the Helmholtz free energy) and is assumed to be a constant for a specific ensemble to be considered canonical.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] However, the probabilities and *F* will vary if different *N*, *V*, *T* are selected.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The free energy *F* serves two roles: first, it provides a normalization factor for the probability distribution (the probabilities, over the complete set of microstates, must add up to one); second, many important ensemble averages can be directly calculated from the function *F*(*N*, *V*, *T*).
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The equations below (in terms of free energy) may be restated in terms of the canonical partition function by simple mathematical manipulations.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] Historically, the canonical ensemble was first described by Boltzmann (who called it a *holode*) in 1884 in a relatively unknown paper.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] It was later reformulated and extensively investigated by Gibbs in 1902.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The canonical ensemble is the ensemble that describes the possible states of a system that is in thermal equilibrium with a heat bath (the derivation of this fact can be found in Gibbs).
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The canonical ensemble applies to systems of any size; while it is necessary to assume that the heat bath is very large (i.e., take a macroscopic limit), the system itself may be small or large.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The condition that the system is mechanically isolated is necessary in order to ensure it does not exchange energy with any external object besides the heat bath.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In general, it is desirable to apply the canonical ensemble to systems that are in direct contact with the heat bath, since it is that contact that ensures the equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] When the total energy is fixed but the internal state of the system is otherwise unknown, the appropriate description is not the canonical ensemble but the microcanonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] For systems where the particle number is variable (due to contact with a particle reservoir), the correct description is the grand canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In statistical physics textbooks for interacting particle systems the three ensembles are assumed to be thermodynamically equivalent: the fluctuations of macroscopic quantities around their average value become small and, as the number of particles tends to infinity, they tend to vanish.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In the latter limit, called the thermodynamic limit, the average constraints effectively become hard constraints.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The assumption of ensemble equivalence dates back to Gibbs and has been verified for some models of physical systems with short-range interactions and subject to a small number of macroscopic constraints.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] Despite the fact that many textbooks still convey the message that ensemble equivalence holds for all physical systems, over the last decades various examples of physical systems have been found for which breaking of ensemble equivalence occurs.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] Moreover, if the system is made up of multiple *similar* parts, then each part has exactly the same distribution as the other parts.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In this way, the canonical ensemble provides exactly the Boltzmann distribution (also known as Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics) for systems of *any number* of particles.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In comparison, the justification of the Boltzmann distribution from the microcanonical ensemble only applies for systems with a large number of parts (that is, in the thermodynamic limit).
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In a system composed of pieces that interact with each other, it is usually not possible to find a way to separate the system into independent subsystems as done in the Boltzmann distribution.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In these systems it is necessary to resort to using the full expression of the canonical ensemble in order to describe the thermodynamics of the system when it is thermostatted to a heat bath.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The canonical ensemble is generally the most straightforward framework for studies of statistical mechanics and even allows one to obtain exact solutions in some interacting model systems.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] A classic example of this is the Ising model, which is a widely discussed toy model for the phenomena of ferromagnetism and of self-assembled monolayer formation, and is one of the simplest models that shows a phase transition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] Lars Onsager famously calculated exactly the free energy of an infinite-sized square-lattice Ising model at zero magnetic field, in the canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The precise mathematical expression for a statistical ensemble depends on the kind of mechanics under consideration—quantum or classical—since the notion of a "microstate" is considerably different in these two cases.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In quantum mechanics, the canonical ensemble affords a simple description since diagonalization provides a discrete set of microstates with specific energies.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The classical mechanical case is more complex as it involves instead an integral over canonical phase space, and the size of microstates in phase space can be chosen somewhat arbitrarily.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] Example of canonical ensemble for a quantum system consisting of one particle in a potential well.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] Plot of all possible states of this system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] A canonical ensemble for this system, for the temperature shown.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The states are weighted exponentially in energy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] Each panel shows an energy-position plot with the various stationary states, along with a side plot showing the distribution of states in energy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] A statistical ensemble in quantum mechanics is represented by a density matrix, denoted by ${\hat {\rho }}$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] where *Ĥ* is the system's total energy operator (Hamiltonian), and exp() is the matrix exponential operator.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The canonical ensemble can alternatively be written in a simple form using bra–ket notation, if the system's energy eigenstates and energy eigenvalues are known.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] where the *E**i* are the energy eigenvalues determined by *Ĥ*|*ψ**i*⟩ = *E**i*|*ψ**i*⟩.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In other words, a set of microstates in quantum mechanics is given by a complete set of stationary states.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The density matrix is diagonal in this basis, with the diagonal entries each directly giving a probability.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] Example of canonical ensemble for a classical system consisting of one particle in a potential well.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] (upper graph) and energy-position space (lower graph).
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The side plot shows the distribution of states in energy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In a system of particles, the number of degrees of freedom *n* depends on the number of particles *N* in a way that depends on the physical situation.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] For a three-dimensional monoatomic gas (not molecules), *n* = 3*N*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In diatomic gases there will also be rotational and vibrational degrees of freedom.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] This integral is taken over the entire phase space.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] In other words, a microstate in classical mechanics is a phase space region, and this region has volume *hnC*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] This means that each microstate spans a range of energy, however this range can be made arbitrarily narrow by choosing *h* to be very small.
[src:statistical-mechanics/canonical-ensemble] The phase space integral can be converted into a summation over microstates, once phase space has been finely divided to a sufficient degree.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Entropy is central to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that the entropy of an isolated system left to spontaneous evolution cannot decrease with time.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] As a result, isolated systems evolve toward thermodynamic equilibrium, where the entropy is highest.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] "High" entropy means that energy is more disordered or dispersed, while "low" entropy means that energy is more ordered or concentrated.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] A consequence of the second law of thermodynamics is that certain processes are irreversible.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The thermodynamic concept was referred to by Scottish scientist and engineer William Rankine in 1850 with the names *thermodynamic function* and *heat-potential*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In 1865, German physicist Rudolf Clausius, one of the leading founders of the field of thermodynamics, defined it as the quotient of an infinitesimal amount of heat to the instantaneous temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] He initially described it as *transformation-content*, in German *Verwandlungsinhalt*, and later coined the term *entropy* from a Greek word for *transformation*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Austrian physicist Ludwig Boltzmann explained entropy as the measure of the number of possible microscopic arrangements or states of individual atoms and molecules of a system that comply with the macroscopic condition of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] He used an analogy with how water falls in a water wheel.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] That was an early insight into the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Carnot reasoned that if the body of the working substance, such as a body of steam, is returned to its original state at the end of a complete engine cycle, "no change occurs in the condition of the working body".
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The first law of thermodynamics, deduced from the heat–friction experiments of James Joule in 1843, expresses the concept of energy and its conservation in all processes; the first law, however, is unsuitable for separately quantifying the effects of friction and dissipation.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In the 1850s and 1860s, German physicist Rudolf Clausius objected to the supposition that no change occurs in the working body, and gave that change a mathematical interpretation, by questioning the nature of the inherent loss of usable heat when work is done, e.g., heat produced by friction.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] He described his observations as a dissipative use of energy, resulting in a *transformation-content* (*Verwandlungsinhalt* in German), of a thermodynamic system or working body of chemical species during a change of state.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] That was in contrast to earlier views, based on the theories of Isaac Newton, that heat was an indestructible particle that had mass.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Clausius discovered that the non-usable energy increases as steam proceeds from inlet to exhaust in a steam engine.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The word was adopted into the English language in 1868.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Later, scientists such as Ludwig Boltzmann, Josiah Willard Gibbs, and James Clerk Maxwell gave entropy a statistical basis.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In 1877, Boltzmann visualized a probabilistic way to measure the entropy of an ensemble of ideal gas particles, in which he defined entropy as proportional to the natural logarithm of the number of microstates such a gas could occupy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The proportionality constant in this definition, called the Boltzmann constant, has become one of the defining universal constants for the modern International System of Units (SI).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Henceforth, the essential problem in statistical thermodynamics has been to determine the distribution of a given amount of energy *E* over *N* identical systems.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Constantin Carathéodory, a Greek mathematician, linked entropy with a mathematical definition of irreversibility, in terms of trajectories and integrability.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In 1865, Clausius named the concept of "the differential of a quantity which depends on the configuration of the system" *entropy* (*Entropie*) after the Greek word for 'transformation'.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] This term was formed by replacing the root of ἔργον ('ergon', 'work') by that of τροπή ('tropy', 'transformation').
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Leon Cooper added that in this way "he succeeded in coining a word that meant the same thing to everybody: nothing".
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The concept of entropy is described by two principal approaches, the macroscopic perspective of classical thermodynamics, and the microscopic description central to statistical mechanics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The classical approach defines entropy in terms of macroscopically measurable physical properties, such as bulk mass, volume, pressure, and temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The statistical definition of entropy defines it in terms of the statistics of the motions of the microscopic constituents of a system — modelled at first classically, e.g.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Newtonian particles constituting a gas, and later quantum-mechanically (photons, phonons, spins, etc.).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The two approaches form a consistent, unified view of the same phenomenon as expressed in the second law of thermodynamics, which has found universal applicability to physical processes.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Many thermodynamic properties are defined by physical variables that define a state of thermodynamic equilibrium, which essentially are state variables.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] State variables depend only on the equilibrium condition, not on the path evolution to that state.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] State variables can be functions of state, also called state functions, in a sense that one state variable is a mathematical function of other state variables.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Often, if some properties of a system are determined, they are sufficient to determine the state of the system and thus other properties' values.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] For example, temperature and pressure of a given quantity of gas determine its state, and thus also its volume via the ideal gas law.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] A system composed of a pure substance of a single phase at a particular uniform temperature and pressure is determined, and is thus a particular state, and has a particular volume.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The fact that entropy is a function of state makes it useful.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In the Carnot cycle, the working fluid returns to the same state that it had at the start of the cycle, hence the change or line integral of any state function, such as entropy, over this reversible cycle is zero.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In contrast, an irreversible process increases the total entropy of the system and surroundings.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Any process that happens quickly enough to deviate from the thermal equilibrium cannot be reversible; the total entropy increases, and the potential for maximum work to be done during the process is lost.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The concept of entropy arose from Rudolf Clausius's study of the Carnot cycle which is a thermodynamic cycle performed by a Carnot heat engine as a reversible heat engine.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] According to Carnot's theorem, a heat engine with two thermal reservoirs can produce a work ${\textstyle W}$ if and only if there is a temperature difference between reservoirs.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Originally, Carnot did not distinguish between heats ${\textstyle Q_{\mathsf {H}}}$ and ${\textstyle Q_{\mathsf {C}}}$ , as he assumed caloric theory to be valid and hence that the total heat in the system was conserved.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] But in fact, the magnitude of heat ${\textstyle Q_{\mathsf {H}}}$ is greater than the magnitude of heat ${\textstyle Q_{\mathsf {C}}}$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The possibility that the Carnot function could be the temperature as measured from a zero point of temperature was suggested by Joule in a letter to Kelvin.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] This allowed Kelvin to establish his absolute temperature scale.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] It is known that a work ${\textstyle W>0}$ produced by an engine over a cycle equals to a net heat ${\textstyle Q_{\Sigma }=\left\vert Q_{\mathsf {H}}\right\vert -\left\vert Q_{\mathsf {C}}\right\vert }$ absorbed over a cycle.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Which means there exists a state function ${\textstyle U}$ with a change of ${\textstyle \mathrm {d} U=\delta Q-\mathrm {d} W}$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] It is called an internal energy and forms a central concept for the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Clausius called this state function *entropy*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Notably, any machine or cyclic process converting heat into work (i.e., heat engine) that is claimed to produce an efficiency greater than the one of Carnot is not viable — due to violation of the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] For further analysis of sufficiently discrete systems, such as an assembly of particles, statistical thermodynamics must be used.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Additionally, descriptions of devices operating near the limit of de Broglie waves, e.g. photovoltaic cells, have to be consistent with quantum statistics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The thermodynamic definition of entropy was developed in the early 1850s by Rudolf Clausius and essentially describes how to measure the entropy of an isolated system in thermodynamic equilibrium with its parts.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Clausius created the term entropy as an extensive thermodynamic variable that was shown to be useful in characterizing the Carnot cycle.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Heat transfer in the isotherm steps (isothermal expansion and isothermal compression) of the Carnot cycle was found to be proportional to the temperature of a system (known as its absolute temperature).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] This relationship was expressed in an increment of entropy that is equal to incremental heat transfer divided by temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Entropy was found to vary in the thermodynamic cycle but eventually returned to the same value at the end of every cycle.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Thus it was found to be a function of state, specifically a thermodynamic state of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] While Clausius based his definition on a reversible process, there are also irreversible processes that change entropy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Following the second law of thermodynamics, entropy of an isolated system always increases for irreversible processes.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The difference between an isolated system and closed system is that energy may *not* flow to and from an isolated system, but energy flow to and from a closed system is possible.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Nevertheless, for both closed and isolated systems, and indeed, also in open systems, irreversible thermodynamics processes may occur.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] According to the Clausius equality, for a reversible cyclic thermodynamic process: $\oint {\frac {\delta Q_{\mathsf {rev}}}{T}}=0$ which means the line integral ${\textstyle \int _{L}{\delta Q_{\mathsf {rev}}/T}}$ is path-independent.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Thus we can define a state function ${\textstyle S}$ , called *entropy*: $\mathrm {d} S={\frac {\delta Q_{\mathsf {rev}}}{T}}$ Therefore, thermodynamic entropy has the dimension of energy divided by temperature, and the unit joule per kelvin (J/K) in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] To find the entropy difference between any two states of the system, the integral must be evaluated for some reversible path between the initial and final states.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Since an entropy is a state function, the entropy change of the system for an irreversible path is the same as for a reversible path between the same two states.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] However, the heat transferred to or from the surroundings is different as well as its entropy change.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] We can calculate the change of entropy only by integrating the above formula.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] To obtain the absolute value of the entropy, we consider the third law of thermodynamics: perfect crystals at the absolute zero have an entropy ${\textstyle S=0}$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] From a macroscopic perspective, in classical thermodynamics the entropy is interpreted as a state function of a thermodynamic system: that is, a property depending only on the current state of the system, independent of how that state came to be achieved.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In any process, where the system gives up $\Delta E$ of energy to the surrounding at the temperature ${\textstyle T}$ , its entropy falls by ${\textstyle \Delta S}$ and at least ${\textstyle T\cdot \Delta S}$ of that energy must be given up to the system's surroundings as a heat.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Otherwise, this process cannot go forward.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In classical thermodynamics, the entropy of a system is defined if and only if it is in a thermodynamic equilibrium (though a chemical equilibrium is not required: for example, the entropy of a mixture of two moles of hydrogen and one mole of oxygen in standard conditions is well-defined).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The statistical definition was developed by Ludwig Boltzmann in the 1870s by analysing the statistical behaviour of the microscopic components of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Boltzmann showed that this definition of entropy was equivalent to the thermodynamic entropy to within a constant factor—known as the Boltzmann constant.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In short, the thermodynamic definition of entropy provides the experimental verification of entropy, while the statistical definition of entropy extends the concept, providing an explanation and a deeper understanding of its nature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The interpretation of entropy in statistical mechanics is the measure of uncertainty, disorder, or *mixedupness* in the phrase of Gibbs, which remains about a system after its observable macroscopic properties, such as temperature, pressure and volume, have been taken into account.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] For a given set of macroscopic variables, the entropy measures the degree to which the probability of the system is spread out over different possible microstates.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In contrast to the macrostate, which characterizes plainly observable average quantities, a microstate specifies all molecular details about the system including the position and momentum of every molecule.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The more such states are available to the system with appreciable probability, the greater the entropy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In statistical mechanics, entropy is a measure of the number of ways a system can be arranged, often taken to be a measure of "disorder" (the higher the entropy, the higher the disorder).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] This definition describes the entropy as being proportional to the natural logarithm of the number of possible microscopic configurations of the individual atoms and molecules of the system (microstates) that could cause the observed macroscopic state (macrostate) of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The constant of proportionality is the Boltzmann constant.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The Boltzmann constant, and therefore entropy, have dimensions of energy divided by temperature, which has a unit of joules per kelvin (J⋅K−1) in the International System of Units (or kg⋅m2⋅s−2⋅K−1 in terms of base units).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The entropy of a substance is usually given as an intensive property — either entropy per unit mass (SI unit: J⋅K−1⋅kg−1) or entropy per unit amount of substance (SI unit: J⋅K−1⋅mol−1).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In a general case the expression is: $S=-k_{\mathsf {B}}\ \mathrm {tr} {\left({\hat {\rho }}\times \ln {\hat {\rho }}\right)}$ where ${\textstyle {\hat {\rho }}}$ is a density matrix, $\mathrm {tr}$ is a trace operator and $\ln$ is a matrix logarithm.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The density matrix formalism is not required if the system is in thermal equilibrium so long as the basis states are chosen to be eigenstates of the Hamiltonian.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] For most practical purposes it can be taken as the fundamental definition of entropy since all other formulae for ${\textstyle S}$ can be derived from it, but not vice versa.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Usually, this assumption is justified for an isolated system in a thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Then in case of an isolated system the previous formula reduces to: $S=k_{\mathsf {B}}\ln {\Omega }$ In thermodynamics, such a system is one with a fixed volume, number of molecules, and internal energy, called a microcanonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The most general interpretation of entropy is as a measure of the extent of uncertainty about a system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The equilibrium state of a system maximizes the entropy because it does not reflect all information about the initial conditions, except for the conserved variables.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] This uncertainty is not of the everyday subjective kind, but rather the uncertainty inherent to the experimental method and interpretative model.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The interpretative model has a central role in determining entropy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The qualifier "for a given set of macroscopic variables" above has deep implications when two observers use different sets of macroscopic variables.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] For example, consider observer A using variables ${\textstyle U}$ , ${\textstyle V}$ , ${\textstyle W}$ and observer B using variables ${\textstyle U}$ , ${\textstyle V}$ , ${\textstyle W}$ , ${\textstyle X}$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] If observer B changes variable ${\textstyle X}$ , then observer A will see a violation of the second law of thermodynamics, since he does not possess information about variable ${\textstyle X}$ and its influence on the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In other words, one must choose a complete set of macroscopic variables to describe the system, i.e. every independent parameter that may change during experiment.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Entropy can also be defined for any Markov processes with reversible dynamics and the detailed balance property.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In Boltzmann's 1896 *Lectures on Gas Theory*, he showed that this expression gives a measure of entropy for systems of atoms and molecules in the gas phase, thus providing a measure for the entropy of classical thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In a thermodynamic system, pressure and temperature tend to become uniform over time because the equilibrium state has higher probability (more possible combinations of microstates) than any other state.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Over time the temperature of the glass and its contents and the temperature of the room become equal.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In other words, the entropy of the room has decreased as some of its energy has been dispersed to the ice and water, of which the entropy has increased.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] However, as calculated in the example, the entropy of the system of ice and water has increased more than the entropy of the surrounding room has decreased.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In an isolated system such as the room and ice water taken together, the dispersal of energy from warmer to cooler always results in a net increase in entropy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Thus, when the "universe" of the room and ice water system has reached a temperature equilibrium, the entropy change from the initial state is at a maximum.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The entropy of the thermodynamic system is a measure of how far the equalisation has progressed.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Thermodynamic entropy is a non-conserved state function that is of great importance in the sciences of physics and chemistry.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Historically, the concept of entropy evolved to explain why some processes (permitted by conservation laws) occur spontaneously while their time reversals (also permitted by conservation laws) do not; systems tend to progress in the direction of increasing entropy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] For isolated systems, entropy never decreases.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] This fact has several important consequences in science: first, it prohibits "perpetual motion" machines; and second, it implies the arrow of entropy has the same direction as the arrow of time.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Increases in the total entropy of system and surroundings correspond to irreversible changes, because some energy is expended as waste heat, limiting the amount of work a system can do.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Unlike many other functions of state, entropy cannot be directly observed but must be calculated.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Absolute standard molar entropy of a substance can be calculated from the measured temperature dependence of its heat capacity.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The molar entropy of ions is obtained as a difference in entropy from a reference state defined as zero entropy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The second law of thermodynamics states that the entropy of an isolated system must increase or remain constant.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Therefore, entropy is not a conserved quantity: for example, in an isolated system with non-uniform temperature, heat might irreversibly flow and the temperature become more uniform such that entropy increases.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Chemical reactions cause changes in entropy and system entropy, in conjunction with enthalpy, plays an important role in determining in which direction a chemical reaction spontaneously proceeds.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Rice University's definition of entropy is that it is "a measurement of a system's disorder and its inability to do work in a system".
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] For instance, a substance at uniform temperature is at maximum entropy and cannot drive a heat engine.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] A substance at non-uniform temperature is at a lower entropy (than if the heat distribution is allowed to even out) and some of the thermal energy can drive a heat engine.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] A special case of entropy increase, the entropy of mixing, occurs when two or more different substances are mixed.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] If the substances are at the same temperature and pressure, there is no net exchange of heat or work – the entropy change is entirely due to the mixing of the different substances.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] At a statistical mechanical level, this results due to the change in available volume per particle with mixing.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] These proofs are based on the probability density of microstates of the generalised Boltzmann distribution and the identification of the thermodynamic internal energy as the ensemble average ${\textstyle U=\left\langle E_{i}\right\rangle }$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Thermodynamic relations are then employed to derive the well-known Gibbs entropy formula.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] However, the equivalence between the Gibbs entropy formula and the thermodynamic definition of entropy is not a fundamental thermodynamic relation but rather a consequence of the form of the generalized Boltzmann distribution.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Thermodynamic state functions are described by ensemble averages of random variables.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] At infinite temperature, all the microstates have the same probability.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that, in general, the total entropy of any system does not decrease other than by increasing the entropy of some other system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Hence, in a system isolated from its environment, the entropy of that system tends not to decrease.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] It follows that heat cannot flow from a colder body to a hotter body without the application of work to the colder body.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] As a result, there is no possibility of a perpetual motion machine.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] It follows that a reduction in the increase of entropy in a specified process, such as a chemical reaction, means that it is energetically more efficient.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] It follows from the second law of thermodynamics that the entropy of a system that is not isolated may decrease.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] An air conditioner, for example, may cool the air in a room, thus reducing the entropy of the air of that system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The heat expelled from the room (the system), which the air conditioner transports and discharges to the outside air, always makes a bigger contribution to the entropy of the environment than the decrease of the entropy of the air of that system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Thus, the total of entropy of the room plus the entropy of the environment increases, in agreement with the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In mechanics, the second law in conjunction with the fundamental thermodynamic relation places limits on a system's ability to do useful work.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The entropy change of a system at temperature ${\textstyle T}$ absorbing an infinitesimal amount of heat ${\textstyle \delta q}$ in a reversible way, is given by ${\textstyle \delta q/T}$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] More explicitly, an energy ${\textstyle T_{R}S}$ is not available to do useful work, where ${\textstyle T_{R}}$ is the temperature of the coldest accessible reservoir or heat sink external to the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Statistical mechanics demonstrates that entropy is governed by probability, thus allowing for a decrease in disorder even in an isolated system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Although this is possible, such an event has a small probability of occurring, making it unlikely.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The applicability of a second law of thermodynamics is limited to systems in or sufficiently near equilibrium state, so that they have defined entropy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Some inhomogeneous systems out of thermodynamic equilibrium still satisfy the hypothesis of local thermodynamic equilibrium, so that entropy density is locally defined as an intensive quantity.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] For such systems, there may apply a principle of maximum time rate of entropy production.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] It states that such a system may evolve to a steady state that maximises its time rate of entropy production.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] This does not mean that such a system is necessarily always in a condition of maximum time rate of entropy production; it means that it may evolve to such a steady state.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The entropy of a system depends on its internal energy and its external parameters, such as its volume.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In the thermodynamic limit, this fact leads to an equation relating the change in the internal energy ${\textstyle U}$ to changes in the entropy and the external parameters.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] This relation is known as the *fundamental thermodynamic relation*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The fundamental thermodynamic relation implies many thermodynamic identities that are valid in general, independent of the microscopic details of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Important examples are the Maxwell relations and the relations between heat capacities.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Thermodynamic entropy is central in chemical thermodynamics, enabling changes to be quantified and the outcome of reactions predicted.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The second law of thermodynamics states that entropy in an isolated system — the combination of a subsystem under study and its surroundings — increases during all spontaneous chemical and physical processes.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The Clausius equation introduces the measurement of entropy change which describes the direction and quantifies the magnitude of simple changes such as heat transfer between systems — always from hotter body to cooler one spontaneously.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Thermodynamic entropy is an extensive property, meaning that it scales with the size or extent of a system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In many processes it is useful to specify the entropy as an intensive property independent of the size, as a specific entropy characteristic of the type of system studied.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Specific entropy may be expressed relative to a unit of mass, typically the kilogram (unit: J⋅kg−1⋅K−1).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Alternatively, in chemistry, it is also referred to one mole of substance, in which case it is called the *molar entropy* with a unit of J⋅mol−1⋅K−1.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Thus, when one mole of substance at about 0 K is warmed by its surroundings to 298 K, the sum of the incremental values of ${\textstyle q_{\mathsf {rev}}/T}$ constitute each element's or compound's standard molar entropy, an indicator of the amount of energy stored by a substance at 298 K.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Entropy change also measures the mixing of substances as a summation of their relative quantities in the final mixture.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Entropy is equally essential in predicting the extent and direction of complex chemical reactions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The spontaneity of a chemical or physical process is governed by the Gibbs free energy change (ΔG), as defined by the equation ΔG = ΔH − TΔS, where ΔH represents the enthalpy change, ΔS the entropy change, and T the temperature in Kelvin.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] A negative ΔG indicates a thermodynamically favorable (spontaneous) process, while a positive ΔG denotes a non-spontaneous one.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] When both ΔH and ΔS are positive (endothermic, entropy-increasing), the reaction becomes spontaneous at sufficiently high temperatures, as the TΔS term dominates.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Conversely, if both ΔH and ΔS are negative (exothermic, entropy-decreasing), spontaneity occurs only at low temperatures, where the enthalpy term prevails.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Reactions with ΔH < 0 and ΔS > 0 (exothermic and entropy-increasing) are spontaneous at all temperatures, while those with ΔH > 0 and ΔS < 0 (endothermic and entropy-decreasing) are non-spontaneous regardless of temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] These principles underscore the interplay between energy exchange, disorder, and temperature in determining the direction of natural processes, from phase transitions to biochemical reactions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] A 2011 study in *Science* estimated the world's technological capacity to store and communicate optimally compressed information normalised on the most effective compression algorithms available in the year 2007, therefore estimating the entropy of the technologically available sources.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The author's estimate that humankind's technological capacity to store information grew from 2.6 (entropically compressed) exabytes in 1986 to 295 (entropically compressed) exabytes in 2007.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The world's technological capacity to receive information through one-way broadcast networks was 432 exabytes of (entropically compressed) information in 1986, to 1.9 zettabytes in 2007.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The world's effective capacity to exchange information through two-way telecommunication networks was 281 petabytes of (entropically compressed) information in 1986, to 65 (entropically compressed) exabytes in 2007.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In chemical engineering, the principles of thermodynamics are commonly applied to "open systems", i.e. those in which heat, work, and mass flow across the system boundary.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In general, flow of heat ${\textstyle {\dot {Q}}}$ , flow of shaft work ${\textstyle {\dot {W}}_{\mathsf {S}}}$ and pressure-volume work ${\textstyle P{\dot {V}}}$ across the system boundaries cause changes in the entropy of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Heat transfer entails entropy transfer ${\textstyle {\dot {Q}}/T}$ , where ${\textstyle T}$ is the absolute thermodynamic temperature of the system at the point of the heat flow.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] If there are mass flows across the system boundaries, they also influence the total entropy of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] This account, in terms of heat and work, is valid only for cases in which the work and heat transfers are by paths physically distinct from the paths of entry and exit of matter from the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] To derive a generalised entropy balanced equation, we start with the general balance equation for the change in any extensive quantity ${\textstyle \theta }$ in a thermodynamic system, a quantity that may be either conserved, such as energy, or non-conserved, such as entropy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The nomenclature "entropy balance" is misleading and often deemed inappropriate because entropy is not a conserved quantity.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] In other words, the term ${\textstyle {\dot {S}}_{\mathsf {gen}}}$ is never a known quantity but always a derived one based on the expression above.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Therefore, the open system version of the second law is more appropriately described as the "entropy generation equation" since it specifies that: ${\dot {S}}_{\mathsf {gen}}\geq 0$ with zero for reversible process and positive values for irreversible one.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] For certain simple transformations in systems of constant composition, the entropy changes are given by simple formulas.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] These equations also apply for expansion into a finite vacuum or a throttling process, where the temperature, internal energy and enthalpy for an ideal gas remain constant.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] provided that the constant-pressure molar heat capacity (or specific heat) ${\textstyle C_{\mathrm {P} }}$ is constant and that no phase transition occurs in this temperature interval.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Similarly at constant volume, the entropy change is: $\Delta S=nC_{\mathrm {V} }\ln {\frac {T}{T_{0}}}$ where the constant-volume molar heat capacity ${\textstyle C_{\mathrm {V} }}$ is constant and there is no phase change.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] At low temperatures near absolute zero, heat capacities of solids quickly drop off to near zero, so the assumption of constant heat capacity does not apply.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Since entropy is a state function, the entropy change of any process in which temperature and volume both vary is the same as for a path divided into two steps – heating at constant volume and expansion at constant temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] Reversible phase transitions occur at constant temperature and pressure.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p01] The reversible heat is the enthalpy change for the transition, and the entropy change is the enthalpy change divided by the thermodynamic temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] As a fundamental aspect of thermodynamics and physics, several different approaches to entropy beyond that of Clausius and Boltzmann are valid.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] In Boltzmann's analysis in terms of constituent particles, entropy is a measure of the number of possible microscopic states (or microstates) of a system in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Entropy is often loosely associated with the amount of order or disorder, or of chaos, in a thermodynamic system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] The traditional qualitative description of entropy is that it refers to changes in the state of the system and is a measure of "molecular disorder" and the amount of wasted energy in a dynamical energy transformation from one state or form to another.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] In this direction, several recent authors have derived exact entropy formulas to account for and measure disorder and order in atomic and molecular assemblies.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] One of the simpler entropy order/disorder formulas is that derived in 1984 by thermodynamic physicist Peter Landsberg, based on a combination of thermodynamics and information theory arguments.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] The concept of entropy can be described qualitatively as a measure of energy dispersal at a specific temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Ambiguities in the terms *disorder* and *chaos*, which usually have meanings directly opposed to equilibrium, contribute to widespread confusion and hamper comprehension of entropy for most students.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] As the second law of thermodynamics shows, in an isolated system internal portions at different temperatures tend to adjust to a single uniform temperature and thus produce equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Physical chemist Peter Atkins, in his textbook *Physical Chemistry*, introduces entropy with the statement that "spontaneous changes are always accompanied by a dispersal of energy or matter and often both".
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] It is possible (in a thermal context) to regard lower entropy as a measure of the *effectiveness* or *usefulness* of a particular quantity of energy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Energy supplied at a higher temperature (i.e. with low entropy) tends to be more useful than the same amount of energy available at a lower temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Mixing a hot parcel of a fluid with a cold one produces a parcel of intermediate temperature, in which the overall increase in entropy represents a "loss" that can never be replaced.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] As the entropy of the universe is steadily increasing, its total energy is becoming less useful.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Eventually, this is theorised to lead to the heat death of the universe.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] A definition of entropy based entirely on the relation of adiabatic accessibility between equilibrium states was given by E.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] This approach has several predecessors, including the pioneering work of Constantin Carathéodory from 1909 and the monograph by R.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] An equivalent approach that extends the operational definition of entropy to the entire nonequilibrium domain was derived from a rigorous formulation of the general axiomatic foundations of thermodynamics by J.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] In the setting of Lieb and Yngvason, one starts by picking, for a unit amount of the substance under consideration, two reference states ${\textstyle X_{0}}$ and ${\textstyle X_{1}}$ such that the latter is adiabatically accessible from the former but not conversely.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Von Neumann established a rigorous mathematical framework for quantum mechanics with his work *Mathematische Grundlagen der Quantenmechanik*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] He provided in this work a theory of measurement, where the usual notion of wave function collapse is described as an irreversible process (the so-called von Neumann or projective measurement).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Using this concept, in conjunction with the density matrix he extended the classical concept of entropy into the quantum domain.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] When viewed in terms of information theory, the entropy state function is the amount of information in the system that is needed to fully specify the microstate of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Entropy is the measure of the amount of missing information before reception.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Often called *Shannon entropy*, it was originally devised by Claude Shannon in 1948 to study the size of information of a transmitted message.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] The definition of information entropy is expressed in terms of a discrete set of probabilities ${\textstyle p_{i}}$ so that: $H(X)=-\sum _{i=1}^{n}{p(x_{i})\log {p(x_{i})}}$ where the base of the logarithm determines the units (for example, the binary logarithm corresponds to bits).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] In the case of transmitted messages, these probabilities were the probabilities that a particular message was actually transmitted, and the entropy of the message system was a measure of the average size of information of a message.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] For the case of equal probabilities (i.e. each message is equally probable), the Shannon entropy (in bits) is just the number of binary questions needed to determine the content of the message.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Most researchers consider information entropy and thermodynamic entropy directly linked to the same concept, while others argue that they are distinct.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Both expressions are mathematically similar.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] If ${\textstyle W}$ is the number of microstates that can yield a given macrostate, and each microstate has the same *a priori* probability, then that probability is ${\textstyle p=1/W}$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Some authors argue for dropping the word entropy for the ${\textstyle H}$ function of information theory and using Shannon's other term, "uncertainty", instead.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] The entropy of a substance can be measured, although in an indirect way.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] The process of measurement goes as follows.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] First, a sample of the substance is cooled as close to absolute zero as possible.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] At such temperatures, the entropy approaches zero – due to the definition of temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Then, small amounts of heat are introduced into the sample and the change in temperature is recorded, until the temperature reaches a desired value (usually 25 °C).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] The obtained data allows the user to integrate the equation above, yielding the absolute value of entropy of the substance at the final temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] This value of entropy is called calorimetric entropy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Although the concept of entropy was originally a thermodynamic concept, it has been adapted in other fields of study, including information theory, psychodynamics, thermoeconomics/ecological economics, and evolution.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Entropy is the only quantity in the physical sciences that seems to imply a particular direction of progress, sometimes called an arrow of time.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] As time progresses, the second law of thermodynamics states that the entropy of an isolated system never decreases in large systems over significant periods of time.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Hence, from this perspective, entropy measurement is thought of as a clock in these conditions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Since the 19th century, a number of philosophers have drawn upon the concept of entropy to develop novel metaphysical and ethical systems.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Examples of this work can be found in the thought of Friedrich Nietzsche and Philipp Mainländer, Claude Lévi-Strauss, Isabelle Stengers, Shannon Mussett, and Drew M.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Chiavazzo et al. proposed that where cave spiders choose to lay their eggs can be explained through entropy minimisation.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Entropy has been proven useful in the analysis of base pair sequences in DNA.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Assuming that a finite universe is an isolated system, the second law of thermodynamics states that its total entropy is continually increasing.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] It has been speculated, since the 19th century, that the universe is fated to a heat death in which all the energy ends up as a homogeneous distribution of thermal energy so that no more work can be extracted from any source.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] If the universe can be considered to have generally increasing entropy, then – as Roger Penrose has pointed out – gravity plays an important role in the increase because gravity causes dispersed matter to accumulate into stars, which collapse eventually into black holes.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] The entropy of a black hole is proportional to the surface area of the black hole's event horizon.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Jacob Bekenstein and Stephen Hawking have shown that black holes have the maximum possible entropy of any object of equal size.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] This makes them likely end points of all entropy-increasing processes, if they are totally effective matter and energy traps.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] However, the escape of energy from black holes might be possible due to quantum activity (see Hawking radiation).
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] The role of entropy in cosmology remains a controversial subject since the time of Ludwig Boltzmann.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Recent work has cast some doubt on the heat death hypothesis and the applicability of any simple thermodynamic model to the universe in general.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Although entropy does increase in the model of an expanding universe, the maximum possible entropy rises much more rapidly, moving the universe further from the heat death with time, not closer.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] This results in an "entropy gap" pushing the system further away from the posited heat death equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Other complicating factors, such as the energy density of the vacuum and macroscopic quantum effects, are difficult to reconcile with thermodynamical models, making any predictions of large-scale thermodynamics extremely difficult.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] Current theories suggest the entropy gap to have been originally opened up by the early rapid exponential expansion of the universe.
[src:statistical-mechanics/entropy-p02] The concept of entropy has been used by Nicholas Georgescu-Roegen in ecological economics, where he coined the term 'entropy pessimism'.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] In physics (in particular in statistical mechanics), the **Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution**, or **Maxwell(ian) distribution**, is a particular probability distribution named after James Clerk Maxwell and Ludwig Boltzmann.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The term "particle" in this context refers to gaseous particles only (atoms or molecules), and the system of particles is assumed to have reached thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The energies of such particles follow what is known as Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics, and the statistical distribution of speeds is derived by equating particle energies with kinetic energy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Mathematically, the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution is the chi distribution with three degrees of freedom (the components of the velocity vector in Euclidean space), with a scale parameter measuring speeds in units proportional to the square root of $T/m$ (the ratio of temperature and particle mass).
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution is a result of the kinetic theory of gases, which provides a simplified explanation of many fundamental gaseous properties, including pressure and diffusion.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution applies fundamentally to particle velocities in three dimensions, but turns out to depend only on the speed (the magnitude of the velocity) of the particles.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] A particle speed probability distribution indicates which speeds are more likely: a randomly chosen particle will have a speed selected randomly from the distribution, and is more likely to be within one range of speeds than another.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The kinetic theory of gases applies to the classical ideal gas, which is an idealization of real gases.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] In real gases, there are various effects (e.g., van der Waals interactions, vortical flow, relativistic speed limits, and quantum exchange interactions) that can make their speed distribution different from the Maxwell–Boltzmann form.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] However, rarefied gases at ordinary temperatures behave very nearly like an ideal gas and the Maxwell speed distribution is an excellent approximation for such gases.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] This is also true for ideal plasmas, which are ionized gases of sufficiently low density.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The distribution was first derived by Maxwell in 1860 on heuristic grounds.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Boltzmann later, in the 1870s, carried out significant investigations into the physical origins of this distribution.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The distribution can be derived on the ground that it maximizes the entropy of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] This probability density function gives the probability, per unit speed, of finding the particle with a speed near v.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] This distribution is used for describing systems in equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] However, most systems do not start out in their equilibrium state.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The evolution of a system towards its equilibrium state is governed by the Boltzmann equation.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The equation predicts that for short range interactions, the equilibrium velocity distribution will follow a Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] To the right is a molecular dynamics (MD) simulation in which 900 hard sphere particles are constrained to move in a rectangle.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] They interact via perfectly elastic collisions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The system is initialized out of equilibrium, but the velocity distribution (in blue) quickly converges to the 2D Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution (in orange).
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The mean speed $\langle v\rangle$ , most probable speed (mode) *v*p, and root-mean-square speed ${\textstyle {\sqrt {\langle v^{2}\rangle }}}$ can be obtained from properties of the Maxwell distribution.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] This works well for nearly ideal, monatomic gases like helium, but also for molecular gases like diatomic oxygen.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] This is because despite the larger heat capacity (larger internal energy at the same temperature) due to their larger number of degrees of freedom, their translational kinetic energy (and thus their speed) is unchanged.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution assumes that the velocities of individual particles are much less than the speed of light, i.e. that $T\ll {\frac {mc^{2}}{k_{\text{B}}}}$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] For electrons, the temperature of electrons must be $T_{e}\ll 5.93\times 10^{9}~\mathrm {K}$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] For distribution of speeds of relativistic particles, see Maxwell–Jüttner distribution.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] After Maxwell, Ludwig Boltzmann in 1872 also derived the distribution on mechanical grounds and argued that gases should over time tend toward this distribution, due to collisions (see H-theorem).
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] He later (1877) derived the distribution again under the framework of statistical thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The derivations in this section are along the lines of Boltzmann's 1877 derivation, starting with a result known as Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics (from statistical thermodynamics).
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics gives the average number of particles found in a given single-particle microstate.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Additionally, the particles are assumed to be in thermal equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The denominator in **equation 1** is a normalizing factor so that the ratios $N_{i}:N$ add up to unity — in other words it is a kind of partition function (for the single-particle system, not the usual partition function of the entire system).
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Because velocity and speed are related to energy, Equation (**1**) can be used to derive relationships between temperature and the speeds of gas particles.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] All that is needed is to discover the density of microstates in energy, which is determined by dividing up momentum space into equal sized regions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The potential energy is taken to be zero, so that all energy is in the form of kinetic energy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] where *p*2 is the square of the momentum vector **p** = [*px*, *py*, *pz*].
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The normalizing constant can be determined by recognizing that the probability of a molecule having *some* momentum must be 1.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The distribution is seen to be the product of three independent normally distributed variables $p_{x}$ , $p_{y}$ , and $p_{z}$ , with variance $mk_{\text{B}}T$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Additionally, it can be seen that the magnitude of momentum will be distributed as a Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution, with ${\textstyle a={\sqrt {mk_{\text{B}}T}}}$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution for the momentum (or equally for the velocities) can be obtained more fundamentally using the H-theorem at equilibrium within the Kinetic theory of gases framework.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] where $d^{3}\mathbf {p}$ is the infinitesimal phase-space volume of momenta corresponding to the energy interval dE.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] At equilibrium, this distribution will hold true for any number of degrees of freedom.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] For example, if the particles are rigid mass dipoles of fixed dipole moment, they will have three translational degrees of freedom and two additional rotational degrees of freedom.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The energy in each degree of freedom will be described according to the above chi-squared distribution with one degree of freedom, and the total energy will be distributed according to a chi-squared distribution with five degrees of freedom.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] This has implications in the theory of the specific heat of a gas.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] which is the Maxwell–Boltzmann velocity distribution.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Like the momentum, this distribution is seen to be the product of three independent normally distributed variables $v_{x}$ , $v_{y}$ , and $v_{z}$ , but with variance ${\textstyle k_{\text{B}}T/m}$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] A notable property of the distribution for the velocity vector is direction-independence, which means that velocity components are normally distributed in any selected direction, not only in three base directions x , y , and z .
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution for the speed follows immediately from the distribution of the velocity vector, above.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Note that the speed is $v={\sqrt {v_{x}^{2}+v_{y}^{2}+v_{z}^{2}}}$ and the volume element in spherical coordinates $dv_{x}\,dv_{y}\,dv_{z}=v^{2}\sin \theta \,dv\,d\theta \,d\phi =v^{2}\,dv\,d\Omega$ where $\phi$ and $\theta$ are the spherical coordinate angles of the velocity vector.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Integration of the probability density function of the velocity over the solid angles $d\Omega$ yields an additional factor of $4\pi$ .
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The derivations show that the validity of the Maxwell–Boltzmann velocity distribution is limited to ideal gases.
[src:statistical-mechanics/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] A generalization of the formula to all gases (ideal and real alike) is known, its derivation starts from the fact that the properties of both ideal and real gases must be independent of the direction.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In physics, a **partition function** describes the statistical properties of a system in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Partition functions are functions of the thermodynamic state variables, such as the temperature and volume.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Most of the aggregate thermodynamic variables of the system, such as the total energy, free energy, entropy, and pressure, can be expressed in terms of the partition function or its derivatives.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The partition function is dimensionless.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Each partition function is constructed to represent a particular statistical ensemble (which, in turn, corresponds to a particular free energy).
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The most common statistical ensembles have named partition functions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The **canonical partition function** applies to a canonical ensemble, in which the system is allowed to exchange heat with the environment at fixed temperature, volume, and number of particles.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The **grand canonical partition function** applies to a grand canonical ensemble, in which the system can exchange both heat and particles with the environment, at fixed temperature, volume, and chemical potential.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Other types of partition functions can be defined for different circumstances; see partition function (mathematics) for generalizations.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The partition function has many physical meanings, as discussed in Meaning and significance.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Initially, let us assume that a thermodynamically large system is in thermal contact with the environment, with a temperature *T*, and both the volume of the system and the number of constituent particles are fixed.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] A collection of this kind of system comprises an ensemble called a canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The appropriate mathematical expression for the canonical partition function depends on the degrees of freedom of the system, whether the context is classical mechanics or quantum mechanics, and whether the spectrum of states is discrete or continuous.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The exponential factor $e^{-\beta E_{i}}$ is otherwise known as the Boltzmann factor.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] There are multiple approaches to deriving the partition function.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The following derivation follows the more powerful and general information-theoretic Jaynesian maximum entropy approach.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] According to the second law of thermodynamics, a system assumes a configuration of maximum entropy at thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Thus the canonical partition function Z becomes $Z\equiv \sum _{i}e^{-\beta E_{i}},$ where $\beta \equiv 1/(k_{\text{B}}T)$ is defined as the thermodynamic beta.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In classical mechanics, the position and momentum variables of a particle can vary continuously, so the set of microstates is actually uncountable.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In *classical* statistical mechanics, it is rather inaccurate to express the partition function as a sum of discrete terms.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In this case we must describe the partition function using an integral rather than a sum.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] To make it into a dimensionless quantity, we must divide it by *h*, which is some quantity with units of action (usually taken to be the Planck constant).
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The reason for the factorial factor *N*! is discussed below.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The extra constant factor introduced in the denominator was introduced because, unlike the discrete form, the continuous form shown above is not dimensionless.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] As stated in the previous section, to make it into a dimensionless quantity, we must divide it by *h*3*N* (where *h* is usually taken to be the Planck constant).
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The dimension of $e^{-\beta {\hat {H}}}$ is the number of energy eigenstates of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In systems with multiple quantum states *s* sharing the same energy *Es*, it is said that the energy levels of the system are degenerate.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The above treatment applies to *quantum* statistical mechanics, where a physical system inside a finite-sized box will typically have a discrete set of energy eigenstates, which we can use as the states *s* above.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In quantum mechanics, the partition function can be more formally written as a trace over the state space (which is independent of the choice of basis): $Z=\operatorname {tr} (e^{-\beta {\hat {H}}}),$ where *Ĥ* is the quantum Hamiltonian operator.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The exponential of an operator can be defined using the exponential power series.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The classical form of *Z* is recovered when the trace is expressed in terms of coherent states and when quantum-mechanical uncertainties in the position and momentum of a particle are regarded as negligible.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Formally, using bra–ket notation, one inserts under the trace for each degree of freedom the identity: ${\boldsymbol {1}}=\int |x,p\rangle \langle x,p|{\frac {dx\,dp}{h}},$ where |*x*, *p*⟩ is a normalised Gaussian wavepacket centered at position *x* and momentum *p*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] If Δ*x* and Δ*p* can be regarded as zero, the action of *Ĥ* reduces to multiplication by the classical Hamiltonian, and *Z* reduces to the classical configuration integral.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] For simplicity, we will use the discrete form of the partition function in this section.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Our results will apply equally well to the continuous form.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Consider a system *S* embedded into a heat bath *B*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Let the total energy of both systems be *E*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Let *pi* denote the probability that the system *S* is in a particular microstate, *i*, with energy *Ei*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Equivalently, *pi* will be proportional to the number of microstates of the heat bath *B* with energy *E* − *Ei*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] We then normalize this by dividing by the total number of microstates in which the constraints we have imposed on the entire system; both S and the heat bath; hold.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In order to demonstrate the usefulness of the partition function, let us calculate the thermodynamic value of the total energy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] This provides us with a method for calculating the expected values of many microscopic quantities.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] We add the quantity artificially to the microstate energies (or, in the language of quantum mechanics, to the Hamiltonian), calculate the new partition function and expected value, and then set *λ* to zero in the final expression.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] This is analogous to the source field method used in the path integral formulation of quantum field theory.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In this section, we will state the relationships between the partition function and the various thermodynamic parameters of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] These results can be derived using the method of the previous section and the various thermodynamic relations.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In general, consider the extensive variable *X* and intensive variable *Y* where *X* and *Y* form a pair of conjugate variables.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The sign will depend on the specific definitions of the variables *X* and *Y*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] An example would be *X* = volume and *Y* = pressure.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Suppose a system is subdivided into *N* sub-systems with negligible interaction energy, that is, we can assume the particles are essentially non-interacting.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] However, there is a well-known exception to this rule.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] If the sub-systems are actually identical particles, in the quantum mechanical sense that they are impossible to distinguish even in principle, the total partition function must be divided by a *N*!
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] This is to ensure that we do not "over-count" the number of microstates.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] While this may seem like a strange requirement, it is actually necessary to preserve the existence of a thermodynamic limit for such systems.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] It may not be obvious why the partition function, as we have defined it above, is an important quantity.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The partition function is a function of the temperature *T* and the microstate energies *E*1, *E*2, *E*3, etc.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The microstate energies are determined by other thermodynamic variables, such as the number of particles and the volume, as well as microscopic quantities like the mass of the constituent particles.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] This dependence on microscopic variables is the central point of statistical mechanics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] With a model of the microscopic constituents of a system, one can calculate the microstate energies, and thus the partition function, which will then allow us to calculate all the other thermodynamic properties of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The partition function can be related to thermodynamic properties because it has a very important statistical meaning.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] This is the reason for calling *Z* the "partition function": it encodes how the probabilities are partitioned among the different microstates, based on their individual energies.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Other partition functions for different ensembles divide up the probabilities based on other macrostate variables.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] As an example: the partition function for the isothermal-isobaric ensemble, the generalized Boltzmann distribution, divides up probabilities based on particle number, pressure, and temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The energy is replaced by the characteristic potential of that ensemble, the Gibbs Free Energy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The letter *Z* stands for the German word *Zustandssumme*, "sum over states".
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The usefulness of the partition function stems from the fact that the macroscopic thermodynamic quantities of a system can be related to its microscopic details through the derivatives of its partition function.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Finding the partition function is also equivalent to performing a Laplace transform of the density of states function from the energy domain to the *β* domain, and the inverse Laplace transform of the partition function reclaims the state density function of energies.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] We can define a **grand canonical partition function** for a grand canonical ensemble, which describes the statistics of a constant-volume system that can exchange both heat and particles with a reservoir.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The reservoir has a constant temperature *T*, and a chemical potential *μ*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The number of microstates in the grand canonical ensemble may be much larger than in the canonical ensemble, since here we consider not only variations in energy but also in particle number.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] An important application of the grand canonical ensemble is in deriving exactly the statistics of a non-interacting many-body quantum gas (Fermi–Dirac statistics for fermions, Bose–Einstein statistics for bosons), however it is much more generally applicable than that.
[src:statistical-mechanics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The grand canonical ensemble may also be used to describe classical systems, or even interacting quantum gases.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In physics, chemistry and biology, a **phase transition** (or **phase change**) is the physical process of transition between one state of a medium and another.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Commonly the term is used to refer to changes among the basic states of matter: solid, liquid, and gas, and in rare cases, plasma.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] A phase of a thermodynamic system and the states of matter have uniform physical properties.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] During a phase transition of a given medium, certain properties of the medium change as a result of the change of external conditions, such as temperature or pressure.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This can be a discontinuous change; for example, a liquid may become gas upon heating to its boiling point, resulting in an abrupt change in volume.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The identification of the external conditions at which a transformation occurs defines the phase transition point.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Phase transitions commonly refer to when a substance transforms between one of the four states of matter to another.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] At the phase transition point for a substance, for instance the boiling point, the two phases involved - liquid and vapor, have identical free energies and therefore are equally likely to exist.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Below the boiling point, the liquid is the more stable state of the two, whereas above the boiling point the gaseous form is the more stable.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] For a single component, the most stable phase at different temperatures and pressures can be shown on a phase diagram.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Such a diagram usually depicts states in equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] A phase transition usually occurs when the pressure or temperature changes and the system crosses from one region to another, like water turning from liquid to solid as soon as the temperature drops below the freezing point.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In exception to the usual case, it is sometimes possible to change the state of a system diabatically (as opposed to adiabatically) in such a way that it can be brought past a phase transition point without undergoing a phase transition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The resulting state is metastable, i.e., less stable than the phase to which the transition would have occurred, but not unstable either.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This occurs in superheating and supercooling, for example.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Metastable states do not appear on usual phase diagrams.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Phase transitions can also occur when a solid changes to a different structure without changing its chemical makeup.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In elements, this is known as allotropy, whereas in compounds it is known as polymorphism.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The change from one crystal structure to another, from a crystalline solid to an amorphous solid, or from one amorphous structure to another (polyamorphs) are all examples of solid to solid phase transitions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The martensitic transformation occurs as one of the many phase transformations in carbon steel and stands as a model for displacive phase transformations.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Order-disorder transitions such as in alpha-titanium aluminides.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] As with states of matter, there is also a metastable to equilibrium phase transformation for structural phase transitions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] A metastable polymorph which forms rapidly due to lower surface energy will transform to an equilibrium phase given sufficient thermal input to overcome an energetic barrier.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Many dynamic, or soft, microporous materials exhibit structural phase transitions between closed and open forms.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Metal–organic frameworks, in particular, have been extensively studied for this behavior.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The phase landscape can be more complex, with intermediate phases discovered.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Further examples show that guest molecules can stabilize specific phases, resulting in crystal configurations that depend on the composition of the surrounding atmosphere.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Phase transitions can also describe the change between different kinds of magnetic ordering.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The most well-known is the transition between the ferromagnetic and paramagnetic phases of magnetic materials, which occurs at what is called the Curie point.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Another example is the transition between differently ordered, commensurate or incommensurate, magnetic structures, such as in cerium antimonide.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] A simplified but highly useful model of magnetic phase transitions is provided by the Ising model.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Phase transitions involving solutions and mixtures are more complicated than transitions involving a single compound.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This is often the case in solid solutions, where the two components are isostructural.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] There are also a number of phase transitions involving three phases: a eutectic transformation, in which a two-component single-phase liquid is cooled and transforms into two solid phases.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The same process, but beginning with a solid instead of a liquid is called a eutectoid transformation.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] A peritectic transformation, in which a two-component single-phase solid is heated and transforms into a solid phase and a liquid phase.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] A peritectoid reaction is a peritectoid reaction, except involving only solid phases.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] A monotectic reaction consists of change from a liquid and to a combination of a solid and a second liquid, where the two liquids display a miscibility gap.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Separation into multiple phases can occur via spinodal decomposition, in which a single phase is cooled and separates into two different compositions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Non-equilibrium mixtures can occur, such as in supersaturation.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Phase transitions occur when the thermodynamic free energy of a system is non-analytic for some choice of thermodynamic variables (cf. phases).
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This condition generally stems from the interactions of a large number of particles in a system, and does not appear in systems that are small.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Phase transitions can occur for non-thermodynamic systems, where temperature is not a parameter.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Examples include: quantum phase transitions, dynamic phase transitions, and topological (structural) phase transitions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In these types of systems other parameters take the place of temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] For instance, connection probability replaces temperature for percolating networks.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Paul Ehrenfest classified phase transitions based on the behavior of the thermodynamic free energy as a function of other thermodynamic variables.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The various solid/liquid/gas transitions are classified as first-order transitions because they involve a discontinuous change in density, which is the (inverse of the) first derivative of the free energy with respect to pressure.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] *Second-order phase transitions* are continuous in the first derivative (the order parameter, which is the first derivative of the free energy with respect to the external field, is continuous across the transition) but exhibit discontinuity in a second derivative of the free energy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Under the Ehrenfest scheme, there could in principle be third, fourth, and higher-order phase transitions, but in practice, only first- and second-order phase transitions are generally observed.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Examples of exceptions to this include the Gross–Witten–Wadia phase transition in 2-D lattice quantum chromodynamics, which is a third-order phase transition, and the Tracy–Widom distribution, which can be interpreted as a third-order transition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The Curie points of many ferromagnetics are also comsidered third-order transitions, as shown by their specific heat having a sudden change in slope.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The concept of the second-order phase transition, was for a while, controversial, as it seemed to require two "sheets" of the Gibbs free energy to osculate exactly, which was considered so unlikely as to likely never occur.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Cornelis Gorter replied the criticism, pointing out that the Gibbs free energy surface might have two sheets on one side, but only one sheet on the other side, creating a forked appearance.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The first example of a phase transition discovered that did not fit into the Ehrenfest classification was the exact solution of the Ising model, discovered in 1944 by Lars Onsager.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The exact specific heat differed from the earlier mean-field approximations, which had predicted that it has a simple discontinuity at critical temperature; instead, the exact specific heat diverged logarithmically at the critical temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In the following decades, the Ehrenfest classification was replaced by a simplified scheme that is able to incorporate such transitions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Related primary research reports have suggested that quenched disorder can broaden a first-order transition: that while transformation is completed over a finite range of temperatures, phenomena like supercooling and superheating survive, and hysteresis is observed on thermal cycling.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In contrast to viscosity, thermal expansion and heat capacity of amorphous materials show a relatively sudden change at the glass transition temperature, a change that enables accurate detection using differential scanning calorimetry measurements.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Several transitions are known as *infinite-order phase transitions*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] They are continuous but break no symmetries.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The most famous example is the Kosterlitz–Thouless transition in the two-dimensional XY model.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Many quantum phase transitions, e.g., in two-dimensional electron gases, belong to this class.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Apart from isolated, simple phase transitions, there exist transition lines as well as multicritical points, when varying external parameters like the magnetic field or composition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The liquid–glass transition is observed in many polymers and other liquids that can be supercooled far below the melting point of the crystalline phase.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] It is not a transition between thermodynamic ground states: it is widely believed that the true ground state is always crystalline.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Glass is a *quenched disorder* state, and its entropy, density, and so on, depend on the thermal history.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Therefore, the glass transition is primarily a dynamic phenomenon: on cooling a liquid, internal degrees of freedom successively fall out of equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Some theoretical methods predict an underlying phase transition in the hypothetical limit of infinitely long relaxation times.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] No direct experimental evidence supports the existence of these transitions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] A disorder-broadened first-order transition occurs over a finite range of temperatures where the fraction of the low-temperature equilibrium phase grows from zero to one (100%) as the temperature is lowered.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This continuous variation of the coexisting fractions with temperature raised interesting possibilities.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] On cooling, some liquids vitrify into a glass rather than transform to the equilibrium crystal phase.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This happens if the cooling rate is faster than a critical cooling rate, and is attributed to the molecular motions becoming so slow that the molecules cannot rearrange into the crystal positions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This slowing down happens below a glass-formation temperature *T*g, which may depend on the applied pressure.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] If the first-order freezing transition occurs over a range of temperatures, and *T*g falls within this range, then there is an interesting possibility that the transition is arrested when it is partial and incomplete.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Extending these ideas to first-order magnetic transitions being arrested at low temperatures, resulted in the observation of incomplete magnetic transitions, with two magnetic phases coexisting, down to the lowest temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] First reported in the case of a ferromagnetic to anti-ferromagnetic transition, such persistent phase coexistence has now been reported across a variety of first-order magnetic transitions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] These include colossal-magnetoresistance manganite materials, magnetocaloric materials, magnetic shape memory materials, and other materials.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The interesting feature of these observations of *T*g falling within the temperature range over which the transition occurs is that the first-order magnetic transition is influenced by magnetic field, just like the structural transition is influenced by pressure.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The relative ease with which magnetic fields can be controlled, in contrast to pressure, raises the possibility that one can study the interplay between *T*g and *T*c in an exhaustive way.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Phase coexistence across first-order magnetic transitions will then enable the resolution of outstanding issues in understanding glasses.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In any system containing liquid and gaseous phases, there exists a special combination of pressure and temperature, known as the critical point, at which the transition between liquid and gas becomes a second-order transition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Near the critical point, the fluid is sufficiently hot and compressed that the distinction between the liquid and gaseous phases is almost non-existent.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This is associated with the phenomenon of critical opalescence, a milky appearance of the liquid due to density fluctuations at all possible wavelengths (including those of visible light).
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Phase transitions often involve a symmetry breaking process.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] For instance, the cooling of a fluid into a crystalline solid breaks continuous translation symmetry: each point in the fluid has the same properties, but each point in a crystal does not have the same properties (unless the points are chosen from the lattice points of the crystal lattice).
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Typically, the high-temperature phase contains more symmetries than the low-temperature phase due to spontaneous symmetry breaking, with the exception of certain accidental symmetries (e.g. the formation of heavy virtual particles, which only occurs at low temperatures).
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] An **order parameter** is a measure of the degree of order across the boundaries in a phase transition system; it normally takes on the value of zero in one phase (usually above the critical point) and nonzero in the other.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] At the critical point, the order parameter susceptibility (the change of an extensive property under variation of an intensive property) will usually diverge.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] An example of an order parameter is the net magnetization in a ferromagnetic system undergoing a phase transition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] For liquid/gas transitions, the order parameter is the difference of the densities.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] From a theoretical perspective, order parameters arise from symmetry breaking.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] When this happens, one needs to introduce one or more extra variables to describe the state of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] For example, in the ferromagnetic phase, one must provide the net magnetization, whose direction was spontaneously chosen when the system cooled below the Curie point.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] However, note that order parameters can also be defined for non-symmetry-breaking transitions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Some phase transitions, such as superconducting and ferromagnetic, can have order parameters for more than one degree of freedom.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In such phases, the order parameter may take the form of a complex number, a vector, or even a tensor, the magnitude of which goes to zero at the phase transition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] There also exist dual descriptions of phase transitions in terms of disorder parameters.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] These indicate the presence of line-like excitations such as vortex- or defect lines.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Symmetry-breaking phase transitions play an important role in cosmology.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] As the universe expanded and cooled, the vacuum underwent a series of symmetry-breaking phase transitions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] For example, the electroweak transition broke the SU(2)×U(1) symmetry of the electroweak field into the U(1) symmetry of the present-day electromagnetic field.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This transition is important to explain the asymmetry between the amount of matter and antimatter in the present-day universe, according to electroweak baryogenesis theory.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Progressive phase transitions in an expanding universe are implicated in the development of order in the universe, as is illustrated by the work of Eric Chaisson and David Layzer.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] See also relational order theories and order and disorder.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Continuous phase transitions are easier to study than first-order transitions due to the absence of latent heat, and they have been discovered to have many interesting properties.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The phenomena associated with continuous phase transitions are called critical phenomena, due to their association with critical points.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Continuous phase transitions can be characterized by parameters known as critical exponents.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The most important one is perhaps the exponent describing the divergence of the thermal correlation length by approaching the transition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] For instance, let us examine the behavior of the heat capacity near such a transition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] We vary the temperature *T* of the system while keeping all the other thermodynamic variables fixed and find that the transition occurs at some critical temperature *T*c.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The heat capacity of amorphous materials has such a behaviour near the glass transition temperature where the universal critical exponent *α* = 0.59 A similar behavior, but with the exponent *ν* instead of *α*, applies for the correlation length.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The critical exponents are not necessarily the same above and below the critical temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] When a continuous symmetry is explicitly broken down to a discrete symmetry by irrelevant (in the renormalization group sense) anisotropies, then some exponents (such as $\gamma$ , the exponent of the susceptibility) are not identical.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] For $\alpha <-1$ , the heat capacity remains differentiable at the transition temperature, although discontinuities appear at higher-order derivatives.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] For $-1\leq \alpha <0$ , the heat capacity has a "kink" at the transition temperature.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This is the behavior of liquid helium at the lambda transition from a normal state to the superfluid state, for which experiments have found *α* = −0.013 ± 0.003.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] At least one experiment was performed in the zero-gravity conditions of an orbiting satellite to minimize pressure differences in the sample.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This experimental value of α agrees with theoretical predictions based on variational perturbation theory.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] For 0 < *α* < 1, the heat capacity diverges at the transition temperature (though, since *α* < 1, the enthalpy stays finite).
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] An example of such behavior is the 3D ferromagnetic phase transition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In the three-dimensional Ising model for uniaxial magnets, detailed theoretical studies have yielded the exponent *α* ≈ +0.110.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Some model systems do not obey a power-law behavior.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] For example, mean field theory predicts a finite discontinuity of the heat capacity at the transition temperature, and the two-dimensional Ising model has a logarithmic divergence.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] However, these systems are limiting cases and an exception to the rule.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Real phase transitions exhibit power-law behavior.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Several other critical exponents, *β*, *γ*, *δ*, *ν*, and *η*, are defined, examining the power law behavior of a measurable physical quantity near the phase transition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] It can be shown that there are only two independent exponents, e.g.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] It is a remarkable fact that phase transitions arising in different systems often possess the same set of critical exponents.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This phenomenon is known as *universality*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] For example, the critical exponents at the liquid–gas critical point have been found to be independent of the chemical composition of the fluid.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] More impressively, but understandably from above, they are an exact match for the critical exponents of the ferromagnetic phase transition in uniaxial magnets.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Such systems are said to be in the same universality class.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Again, the divergence of the correlation length is the essential point.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] There are also other critical phenomena; e.g., besides *static functions* there is also *critical dynamics*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] As a consequence, at a phase transition one may observe *critical slowing down* or *speeding up*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Connected to the previous phenomenon is also the phenomenon of *enhanced fluctuations* before the phase transition, as a consequence of lower degree of stability of the initial phase of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The large *static universality classes* of a continuous phase transition split into smaller *dynamic universality* classes.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In addition to the critical exponents, there are also universal relations for certain static or dynamic functions of the magnetic fields and temperature differences from the critical value.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] A variety of methods are applied for studying the various effects.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Phase transitions play many important roles in biological systems.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In *biological membranes*, gel to liquid crystalline phase transitions play a critical role in physiological functioning of biomembranes.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In gel phase, due to low fluidity of membrane lipid fatty-acyl chains, membrane proteins have restricted movement and thus are restrained in exercise of their physiological role.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Plants depend critically on photosynthesis by chloroplast thylakoid membranes which are exposed cold environmental temperatures.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Thylakoid membranes retain innate fluidity even at relatively low temperatures because of high degree of fatty-acyl disorder allowed by their high content of linolenic acid, 18-carbon chain with 3-double bonds.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Gel-to-liquid crystalline phase transition temperature of biological membranes can be determined by many techniques including calorimetry, fluorescence, spin label electron paramagnetic resonance and NMR by recording measurements of the concerned parameter by at series of sample temperatures.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] A simple method for its determination from 13-C NMR line intensities has also been proposed.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] It has been proposed that some biological systems might lie near critical points.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Examples include neural networks in the salamander retina, bird flocks, gene expression networks in Drosophila, and protein folding.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] However, it is not clear whether or not alternative reasons could explain some of the phenomena supporting arguments for criticality.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] It has also been suggested that biological organisms share two key properties of phase transitions: the change of macroscopic behavior and the coherence of a system at a critical point.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Phase transitions are prominent feature of motor behavior in biological systems.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Spontaneous gait transitions, as well as fatigue-induced motor task disengagements, show typical critical behavior as an intimation of the sudden qualitative change of the previously stable motor behavioral pattern.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The characteristic feature of second order phase transitions is the appearance of fractals in some scale-free properties.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] It has long been known that protein globules are shaped by interactions with water.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] There are 20 amino acids that form side groups on protein peptide chains range from hydrophilic to hydrophobic, causing the former to lie near the globular surface, while the latter lie closer to the globular center.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Twenty fractals were discovered in solvent associated surface areas of > 5000 protein segments.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] The existence of these fractals proves that proteins function near critical points of second-order phase transitions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] In groups of organisms in stress (when approaching critical transitions), correlations tend to increase, while at the same time, fluctuations also increase.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] This effect is supported by many experiments and observations of groups of people, mice, trees, and grassy plants.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] Phase transitions have been hypothesised to occur in social systems viewed as dynamical systems.
[src:statistical-mechanics/phase-transition] A hypothesis proposed in the 1990s and 2000s in the context of peace and armed conflict is that when a conflict that is non-violent shifts to a phase of armed conflict, this is a phase transition from latent to manifest phases within the dynamical system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In physics, **statistical mechanics** is a mathematical framework that applies statistical methods and probability theory to large assemblies of microscopic entities.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Sometimes called **statistical physics** or **statistical thermodynamics**, its applications include many problems in a wide variety of fields such as biology, neuroscience, computer science, information theory and sociology.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Its main purpose is to clarify the properties of matter in aggregate, in terms of physical laws governing atomic motion.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] While classical thermodynamics is primarily concerned with thermodynamic equilibrium, statistical mechanics has been applied in non-equilibrium statistical mechanics to the issues of microscopically modeling the speed of irreversible processes that are driven by imbalances.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Examples of such processes include chemical reactions and flows of particles and heat.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The fluctuation–dissipation theorem is the basic knowledge obtained from applying non-equilibrium statistical mechanics to study the simplest non-equilibrium situation of a steady state current flow in a system of many particles.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In 1738, Swiss physicist and mathematician Daniel Bernoulli published *Hydrodynamica* which laid the basis for the kinetic theory of gases.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In this work, Bernoulli posited the argument, still used to this day, that gases consist of great numbers of molecules moving in all directions, that their impact on a surface causes the gas pressure that we feel, and that what we experience as heat is simply the kinetic energy of their motion.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In 1859, after reading a paper on the diffusion of molecules by Rudolf Clausius, the Scottish physicist Maxwell formulated the Maxwell distribution of molecular velocities, which gave the proportion of molecules having a certain velocity in a specific range.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] This was the first-ever statistical law in physics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Maxwell also gave the first mechanical argument that molecular collisions entail an equalization of temperatures and hence a tendency towards equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Five years later, in 1864, Boltzmann, a young student in Vienna, came across Maxwell's paper and spent much of his life developing the subject further.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical mechanics was initiated in the 1870s with the work of Boltzmann, much of which was collectively published in his 1896 *Lectures on Gas Theory*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Boltzmann's original papers on the statistical interpretation of thermodynamics, the *H*-theorem, transport theory, thermal equilibrium, the equation of state of gases, and similar subjects, occupy about 2,000 pages in the proceedings of the Vienna Academy and other societies.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Boltzmann introduced the concept of an equilibrium statistical ensemble and also investigated for the first time non-equilibrium statistical mechanics, with his *H*-theorem.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The term "statistical mechanics" was coined by the American mathematical physicist Gibbs in 1884.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] "Probabilistic mechanics" might today seem a more appropriate term, but "statistical mechanics" is firmly entrenched.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Shortly before his death, Gibbs published in 1902 *Elementary Principles in Statistical Mechanics*, a book which formalized statistical mechanics as a fully general approach to address all mechanical systems—macroscopic or microscopic, gaseous or non-gaseous.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Gibbs' methods were initially derived in the framework of classical mechanics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] However, they were of such generality that they were found to adapt easily to the later quantum mechanics, and still form the foundation of statistical mechanics to this day.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In physics, two types of mechanics are usually examined: classical mechanics and quantum mechanics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Using these two concepts, the state at any other time, past or future, can in principle be calculated.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical mechanics fills this disconnection between the laws of mechanics and the practical experience of incomplete knowledge, by adding some uncertainty about which state the system is in.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Whereas ordinary mechanics only considers the behaviour of a single state, statistical mechanics introduces the statistical ensemble, which is a large collection of virtual, independent copies of the system in various states.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The statistical ensemble is a probability distribution over all possible states of the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In classical statistical mechanics, the ensemble is a probability distribution over phase points (as opposed to a single phase point in ordinary mechanics), usually represented as a distribution in a phase space with canonical coordinate axes.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In quantum statistical mechanics, the ensemble is a probability distribution over pure states and can be compactly summarized as a density matrix.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] These two meanings are equivalent for many purposes, and will be used interchangeably in this article.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] However the probability is interpreted, each state in the ensemble evolves over time according to the equation of motion.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Thus, the ensemble itself (the probability distribution over states) also evolves, as the virtual systems in the ensemble move through different states.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The ensemble evolution is given by the Liouville equation (classical mechanics) or the von Neumann equation (quantum mechanics).
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] These equations can be derived by applying the mechanical equation of motion separately to each virtual system contained in the ensemble, with the probability of each virtual system conserved over time as it evolves.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] One special class of ensemble is those ensembles that do not evolve over time.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] These ensembles are known as *equilibrium ensembles* and their condition is known as *statistical equilibrium*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical equilibrium occurs if, for each state in the ensemble, the ensemble also contains all of its future and past states with probabilities equal to the probability of being in that state.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] (By contrast, *mechanical equilibrium* is a state with a balance of forces that has ceased to evolve.) The study of equilibrium ensembles of isolated systems is the focus of statistical thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Non-equilibrium statistical mechanics addresses the more general case of ensembles that change over time, and/or ensembles of non-isolated systems.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The primary goal of statistical thermodynamics (also known as equilibrium statistical mechanics) is to derive the classical thermodynamics of materials in terms of the properties of their constituent particles and the interactions between them.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In other words, statistical thermodynamics provides a connection between the macroscopic properties of materials in thermodynamic equilibrium, and the microscopic behaviours and motions occurring inside the material.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Whereas statistical mechanics proper involves dynamics, here the attention is focused on *statistical equilibrium* (steady state).
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical equilibrium does not mean that the particles have stopped moving (mechanical equilibrium), rather, only that the ensemble is not evolving.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] A sufficient (but not necessary) condition for statistical equilibrium with an isolated system is that the probability distribution is a function only of conserved properties (total energy, total particle numbers, etc.).
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] There are many different equilibrium ensembles that can be considered, and only some of them correspond to thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Additional postulates are necessary to motivate why the ensemble for a given system should have one form or another.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] A common approach found in many textbooks is to take the *equal a priori probability postulate*.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The equal a priori probability postulate therefore provides a motivation for the microcanonical ensemble described below.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Other fundamental postulates for statistical mechanics have also been proposed.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] For example, recent studies show that the theory of statistical mechanics can be built without the equal a priori probability postulate.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The entropy as defined by Gibbs entropy formula matches with the entropy as defined in classical thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] There are three equilibrium ensembles with a simple form that can be defined for any isolated system bounded inside a finite volume.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] These are the most often discussed ensembles in statistical thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In the macroscopic limit (defined below) they all correspond to classical thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] describes a system with a precisely given energy and fixed composition (precise number of particles).
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The microcanonical ensemble contains with equal probability each possible state that is consistent with that energy and composition.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The canonical ensemble contains states of varying energy but identical composition; the different states in the ensemble are accorded different probabilities depending on their total energy.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] describes a system with non-fixed composition (uncertain particle numbers) that is in thermal and chemical equilibrium with a thermodynamic reservoir.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The grand canonical ensemble contains states of varying energy and varying numbers of particles; the different states in the ensemble are accorded different probabilities depending on their total energy and total particle numbers.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] For systems containing many particles (the thermodynamic limit), all three of the ensembles listed above tend to give identical behaviour.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] It is then simply a matter of mathematical convenience which ensemble is used.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The Gibbs theorem about equivalence of ensembles was developed into the theory of concentration of measure phenomenon, which has applications in many areas of science, from functional analysis to methods of artificial intelligence and big data technology.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In these cases the correct thermodynamic ensemble must be chosen as there are observable differences between these ensembles not just in the size of fluctuations, but also in average quantities such as the distribution of particles.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The correct ensemble is that which corresponds to the way the system has been prepared and characterized—in other words, the ensemble that reflects the knowledge about that system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Once the partition function for an ensemble has been determined for a given system, that system is considered "solved," as all macroscopic thermodynamic observables can be derived from it via partial derivatives.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Calculating the partition function of a thermodynamic ensemble is often a formidable challenge, however, as it requires performing a summation or integration over every possible microstate available to the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] While certain idealized models allow for exact analytical solutions, most realistic many-body systems are too complex for such a treatment.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Consequently, various approximation techniques—such as mean-field theory, perturbation expansions, or Monte Carlo simulations—are employed to estimate the partition function and compute the average values of physical quantities.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] There are some cases which allow exact solutions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Although some problems in statistical physics can be solved analytically using approximations and expansions, most current research utilizes the large processing power of modern computers to simulate or approximate solutions.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] A common approach to statistical problems is to use a Monte Carlo simulation to yield insight into the properties of a complex system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Monte Carlo methods are important in computational physics, physical chemistry, and related fields, and have diverse applications including medical physics, where they are used to model radiation transport for radiation dosimetry calculations.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The Monte Carlo method examines just a few of the possible states of the system, with the states chosen randomly (with a fair weight).
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] As long as these states form a representative sample of the whole set of states of the system, the approximate characteristic function is obtained.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] As more and more random samples are included, the errors are reduced to an arbitrarily low level.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] All of these processes occur over time with characteristic rates.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] These rates are important in engineering.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The field of non-equilibrium statistical mechanics is concerned with understanding these non-equilibrium processes at the microscopic level.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In principle, non-equilibrium statistical mechanics could be mathematically exact: ensembles for an isolated system evolve over time according to deterministic equations such as Liouville's equation or its quantum equivalent, the von Neumann equation.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] These equations are the result of applying the mechanical equations of motion independently to each state in the ensemble.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] These ensemble evolution equations inherit much of the complexity of the underlying mechanical motion, and so exact solutions are very difficult to obtain.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Moreover, the ensemble evolution equations are fully reversible and do not destroy information (the ensemble's Gibbs entropy is preserved).
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In order to make headway in modelling irreversible processes, it is necessary to consider additional factors besides probability and reversible mechanics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Non-equilibrium mechanics is therefore an active area of theoretical research as the range of validity of these additional assumptions continues to be explored.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] A few approaches are described in the following subsections.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] One approach to non-equilibrium statistical mechanics is to incorporate stochastic (random) behaviour into the system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Stochastic behaviour destroys information contained in the ensemble.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] These correlations appear as chaotic or pseudorandom influences on the variables of interest.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] By replacing these correlations with randomness proper, the calculations can be made much easier.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Another important class of non-equilibrium statistical mechanical models deals with systems that are only very slightly perturbed from equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] With very small perturbations, the response can be analysed in linear response theory.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] A remarkable result, as formalized by the fluctuation–dissipation theorem, is that the response of a system when near equilibrium is precisely related to the fluctuations that occur when the system is in total equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Essentially, a system that is slightly away from equilibrium—whether put there by external forces or by fluctuations—relaxes towards equilibrium in the same way, since the system cannot tell the difference or "know" how it came to be away from equilibrium.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] This provides an indirect avenue for obtaining numbers such as ohmic conductivity and thermal conductivity by extracting results from equilibrium statistical mechanics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Since equilibrium statistical mechanics is mathematically well defined and (in some cases) more amenable for calculations, the fluctuation–dissipation connection can be a convenient shortcut for calculations in near-equilibrium statistical mechanics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] An advanced approach uses a combination of stochastic methods and linear response theory.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] The ensemble formalism can be used to analyze general mechanical systems with uncertainty in knowledge about the state of a system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical physics explains and quantitatively describes superconductivity, superfluidity, turbulence, collective phenomena in solids and plasma, and the structural features of liquid.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] It underlies modern astrophysics and the virial theorem.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In solid state physics, statistical physics aids the study of liquid crystals, phase transitions, and critical phenomena.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Many experimental studies of matter are entirely based on the statistical description of a system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] These include the scattering of cold neutrons, X-ray, visible light, and more.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical physics also plays a role in materials science, nuclear physics, astrophysics, chemistry, biology and medicine (e.g. study of the spread of infectious diseases).
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Analytical and computational techniques derived from statistical physics of disordered systems, can be extended to large-scale problems, including machine learning, e.g. to analyze the weight space of deep neural networks.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical physics is thus finding applications in the area of medical diagnostics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] Quantum statistical mechanics is statistical mechanics applied to quantum mechanical systems.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] In quantum mechanics, a statistical ensemble (probability distribution over possible quantum states) is described by a density operator *S*, which is a non-negative, self-adjoint, trace-class operator of trace 1 on the Hilbert space *H* describing the quantum system.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] This can be shown under various mathematical formalisms for quantum mechanics.
[src:statistical-mechanics/statistical-mechanics] One such formalism is provided by quantum logic.
